bbcode_text = "
[center][b]Help[/b][/center]

SCRUM is used by a large number of organizations that seek to make the product development process more agile. This game is intended to help the player get acquainted with some of the practices of this framework, but is probably not completely accurate: some simplifications have been made to make the game more fun.

SCRUM is designed for small teams whose work is divided into fixed periods, called sprints, lasting from 1 week to 1 month. A team includes a product owner, a SCRUM master and developers. The product owner represents the interests of the stakeholders and the users, is responsible for adding new user stories to the project backlog (a list of features that aren't implemented yet) and prioritizing them. The team of developers organizes itself to achieve the sprint goals. The SCRUM master teaches the team about SCRUM practices, helps with self-organization, protects developers from distractions and hosts a daily 15-minute meeting, during which each of the developers talks briefly about the work they've done the previous working day, what they plan to work on today and about any impediments that may be slowing them down.

During a sprint planning meeting, the team chooses so called user stories — some features that need to be implemented. The difficulty of implementing a user story is usually subjectively measured in story points using the rounded Fibonacci sequence (1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, 20). At a sprint review at the end of a sprint the team presents the current state of the product to the client and receives feedback. After that, a sprint retrospective meeting is held between the developers and the SCRUM master to discuss any organizational problems that arised and how the workflow could be improved.

To better understand how the team is doing, the SCRUM master may use multiple metrics, such as:
• A burndown chart — a graphical representation of the work already completed and the work remaining. In this game the red line in the chart represents the actual burndown and the green one serves as a benchmark
• A сumulative flow diagram — a diagram that represents the work completed, planned and in progress
• A velocity chart — a diagram that shows the number of story points completed per sprint (only the user stories with all tasks completed are taken into account)"
